{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.24,0.05,0.33,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111096"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5193"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45148"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111096"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a seven-day history of an abnormally heavy period that occurred on day 20 of her menstrual cycle. She had to change her pad every three hours due to heavy soaking. Over the last few months she has been having episodes of hot flushes. There has been no abnormal vaginal discharge, dyspareunia or weight loss. She has been married for 15 years, with no other sexual partners and reports always using barrier contraception. She has had two uncomplicated pregnancies resulting in live births. Her last cervical screening test two years ago was normal. She has no significant medical history and there is no relevant family history. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical co-test and pelvic ultrasound scan","Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound scan","Uterine pipelle biopsy and hysteroscopy","Serum follicle-stimulating hormone and oestradiol","Nucleic acid amplification test and cervical co-test"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main concern for this 47-year-old woman is the heavy, irregular menstrual bleeding. Potential causes such as perimenopause, cervical cancer, fibroids and endometrial polyps must be considered. Her age, menorrhagia, hot flushes, and cycle irregularity suggest perimenopause is most likely. While this is a clinical diagnosis, investigations should still be considered to exclude other causes for her bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical co-test and pelvic ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation. A cervical co-test involving liquid-based cytology and testing for human papillomavirus (HPV) is specifically indicated to investigate abnormal vaginal bleeding in women over 45, as it allows detection of cervical cancer and precancerous changes that may be missed by HPV testing alone. Irrespective of how recent the patients cervical screening was performed, a cervical co-test should always be performed to investigate abnormal symptoms that may indicate cervical cancer, as cervical screening is only performed in asymptomatic individuals. A pelvic ultrasound scan is non-invasive and can detect structural abnormalities like fibroids and abnormal endometrial appearances suggesting polyps, hyperplasia or dysplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal and pelvic ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessary in this case. While a pelvic ultrasound is appropriate, an abdominal ultrasound would not provide additional useful information for investigating abnormal uterine bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine pipelle biopsy and hysteroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E are more invasive procedures. They are typically performed following an abnormal ultrasound to confirm findings or obtain targeted biopsies. These are not routinely indicated as first-line investigations for abnormal perimenopausal bleeding unless there are specific risk factors or red flag features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicle-stimulating hormone and oestradiol\u003C/strong\u003E levels can fluctuate during perimenopause, making them unreliable tests for diagnosing this condition. Perimenopause is primarily a clinical diagnosis based on symptoms and menstrual irregularities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enucleic acid amplification test (NAAT)\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect sexually transmitted infections like chlamydia and gonorrhoea. While these can cause pelvic inflammatory disease and heavy menstrual bleeding, this is less likely given her limited sexual history. If needed, these can be tested on the cervical co-test sample.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, a cervical co-test and pelvic ultrasound scan provide the most comprehensive initial assessment for a perimenopausal woman with abnormal uterine bleeding, allowing for evaluation of both cervical pathology and structural causes of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perimenopause is a clinical diagnosis and cannot be relied on to exclude other potential causes of perimenopausal bleeding.","A cervical co-test should be performed in women with abnormal perimenopausal bleeding to exclude cervical pathology. Cervical screening test is not sufficient in symptomatic patients.","Pelvic ultrasound is an appropriate initial investigation for abnormal uterine bleeding in perimenopausal women to assess for structural causes."],"references":["Cancer Australia. Abnormal vaginal bleeding in pre-, peri- and post-menopausal women: a diagnostic guide for general practitioners and gynaecologists [Online]. 2011. Available at: https://cancerwa.asn.au/assets/public/2023/12/ncgc_a3_menopause_chart_june_2012_final.pdf","Menopause symptoms. In: The Royal Women\u0027s Hospital [online]. [cited 2023 Apr 13]. Available at: https://www.thewomens.org.au/health-information/menopause-information/menopause-symptoms/","Mishra D, Sultan S. FIGO\u0027s PALM-COEIN Classification of Abnormal Uterine Bleeding: A Clinico-histopathological Correlation in Indian Setting. J Obstet Gynaecol India. 2017;67(2):119-25. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28405119/","Delamater L, Santoro N. Management of the Perimenopause. Clin Obstet Gynecol. 2018;61(3):419-32. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6082400/","Roeske L .GPs\u2019 guide to completing a cervical screening pathology request form. In: RACGP [online]. 2018 [cited 2023 Sep 8]. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/gp-opinion/guide-to-completing-cervical-screening-pathology-r"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T20:12:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T20:12:33+09:30"},"re